        </section>
        <section class="exec eq-walk" aria-label="uTerm pipeline to quantum integration readiness">
          <p class="kicker">uTerm → Quantum Integration Readiness Gate</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Gate A (signal fidelity):</strong> `uterm` command stream exports deterministic prefix + steno traces with `F_rt` above release threshold.</li>
            <li><strong>Gate B (dispatch safety):</strong> `.qbit` artifacts pass preflight GO/WARN policy and backend compatibility checks before QPU queueing.</li>
            <li><strong>Gate C (closed-loop memory):</strong> memory reinjection and retrieval score deltas are measured per iteration and attached to the equation matrix row IDs.</li>
            <li><strong>Gate D (boardroom evidence):</strong> each milestone review includes updated local figure assets, candlestick metric bars, and run metadata for reproducibility.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <h3>3. Deployment Pattern for .qhtml</h3>
        <p>The landing is intentionally structured as a publication-grade PWA document: semantic sections, dense typography, justified narrative blocks, and a sticky expansion rail that keeps technical context available while reading. This supports desktop and mobile reading, and mirrors cleanly into launch announcements without layout drift.</p>

        <h3>3.1 Quantum Race Dynamics</h3>
        <p>The visual transport layer follows a race-wave interpretation of the communication cycle: Bloch-field coherence, torn-mesh constraints, and dot-flow sampling evolve together under one shared waveform. This mirrors the system objective where macro state (Μ) is not isolated from local operators (μ); instead, all lanes update from the same cycle clock, making phase drift, queue transitions, and retrieval-memory reinjection observable as one coupled dynamic rather than separate effects.</p>

        <h3 id="targets">4. Publication + Distribution Targets</h3>
        <p>For final output, treat publication as a two-track release: (A) peer-reviewed research visibility, and (B) production-grade software distribution with explicit licensing and citation metadata.</p>
